.\}.PP
\fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR is invoked to get the \fIgen_statem\fR status.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
The \fIgen_statem\fR process terminates abnormally and logs an error.

.RE

.PP
This function is useful for changing the form and appearance of the \fIgen_statem\fR status for these cases.  A callback module wishing to change the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR return value and how its status appears in termination error logs, exports an instance of \fIModule:format_status/1\fR, which will get a map \fIStatus\fR that describes the current state of the \fIgen_statem\fR, and shall return a map \fINewStatus\fR containing the same keys as the input map, but it may transform some values.

.PP
One use case for this function is to return compact alternative state representations to avoid having large state terms printed in log files. Another is to hide sensitive data from being written to the error log.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
format_status(Status) ->
  maps:map(
    fun(state,State) ->
            maps:remove(private_key, State);
       (message,{password, _Pass}) ->
            {password, removed};
       (_,Value) ->
            Value
    end, Status).

.fi

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis callback is optional, so a callback module does not need to export it.  The \fIgen_statem\fR module provides a default implementation of this function that returns \fI{State, Data}\fR. If this callback is exported but fails, to hide possibly sensitive data, the default function will instead return \fI{State, Info}\fR, where \fIInfo\fR says nothing but the fact that \fIModule:format_status/2\fR has crashed.



.RE
.B
\fBformat_status/2\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: the callback gen_statem:format_status(_,_) is deprecated; use format_status/1 instead
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Format/limit the status value.

.PP
This function is called by a \fIgen_statem\fR process in in order to format/limit the server state for debugging and logging purposes.

.PP
It is called in the following situations:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
One of \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR is invoked to get the \fIgen_statem\fR status. \fIOpt\fR is set to the atom \fInormal\fR for this case.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
The \fIgen_statem\fR terminates abnormally and logs an error. \fIOpt\fR is set to the atom \fIterminate\fR for this case.

.RE

.PP
This function is useful for changing the form and appearance of the \fIgen_statem\fR status for these cases.  A callback module wishing to change the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR return value and how its status appears in termination error logs, should export an instance of \fIModule:format_status/2\fR, that returns a term describing the current status of the \fIgen_statem\fR.

.PP
\fIPDict\fR is the current value of the process dictionary of the \fIgen_statem\fR.

.PP
\fIState\fR is the internal state of the \fIgen_statem\fR.

.PP
\fIData\fR is the internal server data of the \fIgen_statem\fR.

.PP
The function is to return \fIStatus\fR, a term that contains the appropriate details of the current state and status of the \fIgen_statem\fR.  There are no restrictions of the form \fIStatus\fR can take, but for the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR case (when \fIOpt\fR is \fInormal\fR), the recommended form for the \fIStatus\fR value is \fI[{data, [{"State", Term}]}]\fR, where \fITerm\fR provides relevant details of the \fIgen_statem\fR state.  Following this recommendation is not required, but it makes the callback module status consistent with the rest of the \fIsys:get_status/1,2\fR return value.

.PP
One use for this function is to return compact alternative state representations to avoid having large state terms printed in log files. Another use is to hide sensitive data from being written to the error log.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis callback is optional, so a callback module does not need to export it.  The \fIgen_statem\fR module provides a default implementation of this function that returns \fI{State, Data}\fR. If this callback is exported but fails, to hide possibly sensitive data, the default function will instead return \fI{State, Info}\fR, where \fIInfo\fR says nothing but the fact that \fIModule:format_status/2\fR has crashed.



.RE
.B
\fBhandle_event/4\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
\fIState callback\fR in \fIcallback mode\fR \fIhandle_event_function\fR.

.PP
Whenever a \fIgen_statem\fR receives an event from \fIcall/2,3\fR, \fIcast/2\fR, or as a normal process message, this function is called.

.PP
If \fIEventType\fR is \fI{call, From}\fR, the caller waits for a reply.  The reply can be sent from this or from any other \fIstate callback\fR by returning with \fI{reply, From, Reply}\fR in \fIActions\fR, in \fIReplies\fR, or by calling \fIreply(From, Reply)\fR.

.PP
If this function returns with a next state that does not match equal (\fI=/=\fR) to the current state, all postponed events are retried in the next state.

.PP
For options that can be set and actions that can be done by \fIgen_statem\fR after returning from this function, see \fIaction/0\fR.

.PP
When the \fIgen_statem\fR runs with \fIstate enter calls\fR, this function is also called with arguments \fI(enter, OldState, ...)\fR during every \fIstate change\fR.  In this case there are some restrictions on the actions that may be returned:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIpostpone/0\fR is not allowed since a \fIstate enter call\fR is not an event so there is no event to postpone.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fI{next_event, _, _}\fR is not allowed since using \fIstate enter calls\fR should not affect how events are consumed and produced.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
It is not allowed to change states from this call. Should you return \fI{next_state, NextState, ...}\fR with \fINextState =/= State\fR the \fIgen_statem\fR crashes.

.PP
Note that it is actually allowed to use \fI{repeat_state, NewData, ...}\fR although it makes little sense since you immediately will be called again with a new \fIstate enter call\fR making this just a weird way of looping, and there are better ways to loop in Erlang.

.PP
If you do not update \fINewData\fR and have some loop termination condition, or if you use \fI{repeat_state_and_data, _}\fR or \fIrepeat_state_and_data\fR you have an infinite loop!

.PP
You are advised to use \fI{keep_state, ...}\fR, \fI{keep_state_and_data, _}\fR or \fIkeep_state_and_data\fR since changing states from a \fIstate enter call\fR is not possible anyway.

.RE

.PP
Note the fact that you can use \fIthrow\fR to return the result, which can be useful.  For example to bail out with \fIthrow(keep_state_and_data)\fR from deep within complex code that cannot return \fI{next_state, State, Data}\fR because \fIState\fR or \fIData\fR is no longer in scope.


.RE
.B
\fBinit(Args)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Initialize the state machine.

.PP
Whenever a \fIgen_statem\fR is started using \fIstart_link/3,4\fR, \fIstart_monitor/3,4\fR, or \fIstart/3,4\fR, this function is called by the new process to initialize the implementation state and server data.

.PP
\fIArgs\fR is the \fIArgs\fR argument provided to that start function.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that if the \fIgen_statem\fR is started through \fIproc_lib\fR and \fIenter_loop/4,5,6\fR, this callback will never be called.  Since this callback is not optional it can in that case be implemented as:

.IP
.nf
-spec init(_) -> no_return().
init(Args) -> erlang:error(not_implemented, [Args]).

.fi



.RE
.B
\fBterminate/3\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Handle state machine termination.

.PP
This function is called by a \fIgen_statem\fR when it is about to terminate. It is to be the opposite of \fIModule:init/1\fR and do any necessary cleaning up.  When it returns, the \fIgen_statem\fR terminates with \fIReason\fR.  The return value is ignored.

.PP
\fIReason\fR is a term denoting the stop reason and \fIState\fR is the internal state of the \fIgen_statem\fR.

.PP
\fIReason\fR depends on why the \fIgen_statem\fR is terminating.  If it is because another callback function has returned, a stop tuple \fI{stop, Reason}\fR in \fIActions\fR, \fIReason\fR has the value specified in that tuple. If it is because of a failure, \fIReason\fR is the error reason.

.PP
If the \fIgen_statem\fR is part of a supervision tree and is ordered by its supervisor to terminate, this function is called with \fIReason = shutdown\fR if both the following conditions apply:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
The \fIgen_statem\fR process has been set to trap exit signals.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
The shutdown strategy as defined in the supervisor's child specification is an integer time-out value, not \fIbrutal_kill\fR.

.RE

.PP
Even if the \fIgen_statem\fR is \fInot\fR part of a supervision tree, this function is called if it receives an \fI'EXIT'\fR message from its parent. \fIReason\fR is the same as in the \fI'EXIT'\fR message.

.PP
If the \fIgen_statem\fR process is not set up to trap exit signals it is immediately terminated, just like any process, and this function is not called.

.PP
Notice that for any other reason than \fInormal\fR, \fIshutdown\fR, or \fI{shutdown, Term}\fR, the \fIgen_statem\fR is assumed to terminate because of an error and an error report is issued using \fIlogger\fR.

.PP
When the \fIgen_statem\fR process exits, an exit signal with the same reason is sent to linked processes and ports, just as for any process.


.RE
